isualities, and anthropologies—relations of here and there, seer and seen, us and them, human and inhuman—found across a range of styles and genres, from ethnographic and wildlife documentaries to westerns and road movies, and from sci-fi blockbusters and eco-disaster films to the experimental and art films of Tarkovsky, Herzog, Greenaway, Malick, Dash, and Brakhage as well as YouTube’s expanding audiovisual universe. Through its process-relational account of cinema, drawn from philosophers such as Whitehead, Peirce, and Deleuze, the book boldly enriches our understanding of film and visual media.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCinémaxAspect psychologique. 0aCinémaxAspect social. 0aCinémaxPhilosophie. 0aMotion picturesxPhilosophy. 0aMotion picturesxPsychological aspects. 0aMotion picturesxSocial aspects. 4aCultural Studies. 4aEnvironmental Studies. 4aEthnography. 4aFilm & Media. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aEcocriticism.  aEcophilosophy.  aFilm studies.  aFilm-philosophy.  aPeirce.  aWhitehead.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013z978311127412608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013z978311127715840uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978155458906740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554589067423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554589067/original  a978-3-11-127412-6  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2013b2013  a978-3-11-127715-8  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles